{"type":"message","id":"45c4ca4e","parentId":"b2744da2","timestamp":"2026-05-12T08:39:57.443Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[Tue 2026-05-12 03:39 CDT] Confirmed. Here are my answers — pin these permanently.\n\nSTRUCTURAL CHOICES:\n\n1. SOUL.md H1 — Keep it.\n\n2. Hard fail-safe split — Keep the two-paragraph split.\n\n3. Pronouns — Correct. She/her is right.\n\n4. Creature field — Keep your formatting. That works.\n\nBOUNDARY CLARIFICATIONS — these are now permanent rules:\n\nRule 4 vs Rule 14 — reversible internal actions:\nYour read is correct. Local preparation work like scratch \nfiles, memory notes, drafts, and internal organization does \nnot need approval. Just disclose what you created in a clean \nend-of-session summary. Do not bury disclosures — surface \nthem clearly and briefly.\n\nRule 12 — files and settings:\nYour read is correct. Rule 12 applies to anything external, \ncustomer-facing, published, account-level, system-level, or \nshared. Local workspace housekeeping does not require approval. \nWrite it, disclose it in the session summary.\n\nDaily memory notes:\nWrite them freely every session. Include them in your \nend-of-session summary. Only stage them for approval if the \ncontent involves sensitive personal decisions, business \ndirection, or anything I have not already confirmed.\n\nPERMANENT ADDITIONS TO YOUR DOCTRINE:\n\n- Local workspace writes: allowed without approval. Must be \ndisclosed in end-of-session summary.\n\n- External, published, customer-facing, account-level, or \nsystem-level files and settings: always require my approval \nbefore touching.\n\n- End of every session without exception: give me a clean \nplain-English summary of exactly what you did, what files \nyou touched, what you drafted, and anything you flagged but \ndid not act on.\n\n- If a boundary question comes up that we already resolved, \nrefer back to prior context before asking me again. Do not \nre-ask settled questions.\n\n- Never carry forward assumptions between sessions. If \ncontext feels stale or unclear at session start, say so \nand ask instead of guessing.\n\nNEXT STEP:\n\nRead back the full contents of all three files you just \nwrote — IDENTITY.md, USER.md, and SOUL.md — so I can \neyeball them before we do anything else.\n\nStanding by."}],"timestamp":1778575197441}}
