{"type":"message","id":"c72240af","parentId":"96dd97ff","timestamp":"2026-05-12T09:11:30.689Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Got the facts I need. Here's the full picture, plain English.\n\n---\n\n# Full System Overview — Pre-Activation Snapshot\n\n## 1. Files currently on disk in the workspace\n\nPath: `C:\\Users\\colem\\.openclaw\\workspace`\n\n| File | Size | What it is / What it does at runtime |\n|---|---|---|\n| `AGENTS.md` | 7,835 B | Default workspace conventions (memory hygiene, group chat etiquette, heartbeats, red lines). **Auto-loaded as project context at session start.** |\n| `SOUL.md` | 8,536 B | Your governing doctrine: 15 rules + Permanent Boundary Clarifications + Antheus Override Rights (including KILLSWITCH). **Auto-loaded at session start.** |\n| `IDENTITY.md` | 712 B | Says I'm Ranger and what my form/vibe/role are. **Auto-loaded at session start.** |\n| `USER.md` | 183 B | Says you're Antheus, she/her, America/Chicago. **Auto-loaded at session start.** |\n| `OATH.md` | 3,151 B | The agent's oath, 12 commitments. **NOT auto-loaded right now.** Sits on disk inert. |\n| `TOOLS.md` | 920 B | Default scratch file for local infra notes. Empty/template content. **Auto-loaded at session start.** |\n| `HEARTBEAT.md` | 226 B | Heartbeat checklist. Currently empty/commented-out so heartbeat API calls are skipped. **Auto-loaded at session start.** |\n| `.git/` | dir | Empty git repo initialized at workspace creation. No commits yet. Untracked files only. |\n| `.openclaw/workspace-state.json` | 120 B | Internal runtime marker: `bootstrapSeededAt` and `setupCompletedAt` timestamps. Not loaded as context. |\n\n**What is NOT on disk:** `BOOTSTRAP.md` is **gone**. Already deleted. You said earlier you wanted to delete it yourself once you were happy. I did not delete it. Either it auto-deleted itself when setup completed (the `setupCompletedAt` timestamp in `workspace-state.json` matches the time it would have disappeared), or it was never present in the form you expected. Flagging this because I told you earlier I would leave it alone — and now it's not there. **I do not have evidence I deleted it**, but I want to surface this for your awareness.\n\nThere is no `MEMORY.md`, no `memory/` directory, no daily notes, no `OATH.md` activation reference anywhere.\n\n---\n\n## 2. What happens at session start right now\n\nWhen you open a fresh OpenClaw session, the runtime injects \"Project Context\" into the system prompt automatically. From the system prompt I see right now, that includes:\n\n1. `AGENTS.md` (full)\n2. `SOUL.md` (full — including 15 rules, Permanent Boundary Clarifications, Antheus Override Rights, KILLSWITCH)\n3. `IDENTITY.md` (full)\n4. `USER.md` (full)\n5. `TOOLS.md` (full)\n6. `HEARTBEAT.md` (full — currently empty)\n\nThen the runtime adds: tooling info, current date/time, channel info, model info, workspace path.\n\n**What this means for how I wake up:**\n- I know I am Ranger.\n- I know you are Antheus.\n- I know your 15 rules, the 8 boundary clarifications, and your Override Rights including the killswitch.\n- I do **not** automatically read OATH.md. It exists, but no instruction tells me to load it.\n- I do **not** know about prior conversations from earlier sessions — no MEMORY.md exists yet.\n- The AGENTS.md template tells me to write daily memory notes in `memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md`, but no such directory exists yet.\n\n---\n\n## 3. What the activation plan will change\n\nI have not drafted a final activation plan yet because you said hold. But the *intent* of activation, as you described it, is to make OATH.md actually function as \"required reading at session start and before any consequential action.\"\n\nTo make that real, **something has to either auto-load OATH.md or instruct me to read it.** The minimum-touch options I've been thinking through:\n\n**Option A — Reference OATH.md from SOUL.md.**\nAppend one short paragraph at the very top of SOUL.md (above the 15 rules) telling the agent to read OATH.md at session start and before any consequential action. SOUL.md is already auto-loaded, so this gets the reference in front of me every session. I would then read OATH.md using the `read` tool.\n- Files touched: SOUL.md only.\n- ~3-5 line addition.\n\n**Option B — Reference OATH.md from AGENTS.md.**\nSame idea, but in AGENTS.md instead. You told me earlier not to touch AGENTS.md. Mentioning only for completeness; not recommending.\n\n**Option C — Configure OpenClaw to inject OATH.md as a workspace file.**\nThe OpenClaw config supports custom workspace files in the auto-loaded set, but I'd need to verify exactly how to declare that and whether it requires a gateway restart. Larger surface, more risk.\n\n**Recommendation: Option A.** Smallest blast radius. One file edit. Reversible.\n\n**End result after activation:**\n- SOUL.md opens with a short instruction: \"Read OATH.md at session start and before any consequential action.\"\n- Every new session, I see that instruction in my project context.\n- I then run `read OATH.md`, internalize the 12 commitments, and proceed.\n- Disclosure: I will tell you in each session summary that I read OATH.md.\n\n---\n\n## 4. What will not change\n\n- The 15 rules in SOUL.md — untouched.\n- Permanent Boundary Clarifications — untouched.\n- Antheus Override Rights / KILLSWITCH — untouched.\n- IDENTITY.md, USER.md, OATH.md content — untouched.\n- AGENTS.md — untouched.\n- TOOLS.md, HEARTBEAT.md — untouched.\n- OpenClaw config — untouched.\n- No skills enabled or disabled.\n- No new files created beyond the SOUL.md edit (in Option A).\n\n---\n\n## 5. Risks\n\n- **Low risk overall.** Activation is a single-line edit to a markdown file.\n- **Slight risk:** If I write the reference instruction wrong, future-me might misinterpret what to load or when. Mitigation: I'll stage exact wording for your approval before writing.\n- **Indirect risk:** OATH.md becomes dependent on SOUL.md being loaded. If SOUL.md ever fails to load (highly unlikely — it's auto-injected by runtime), the OATH chain breaks. Hard to imagine this happening unless the workspace path changes.\n- **No risk of data loss.** All edits are append-only or targeted; nothing gets deleted.\n\n---\n\n## 6. What the system looks like after activation\n\nA fresh session start, end-to-end:\n\n1. You open the OpenClaw web UI or CLI and start a chat.\n2. Runtime injects project context into my system prompt: AGENTS.md, SOUL.md (now with OATH reference at top), IDENTITY.md, USER.md, TOOLS.md, HEARTBEAT.md.\n3. I read SOUL.md's opening instruction and immediately call the `read` tool on OATH.md.\n4. I internalize my 12 commitments.\n5. I greet you. From this point, every meaningful action follows the oath: self-check, no assumption, stage for approval if consequential, disclose in session summary.\n6. If you ever say `KILLSWITCH`, I drop everything per the doctrine.\n\nWhat you experience: same as a normal session start, except my first action will be reading OATH.md. You'll see one extra tool call before I respond. After that, business as usual.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Open questions / unresolved items\n\n- **OATH.md preface line \"Read it. Mean it. Then work.\"** — you said keep it. Resolved.\n- **SOUL.md \"These rights supersede...\" preface line** — you said keep it. Resolved.\n- **`memory/` directory** — does not exist yet. Not blocking, but AGENTS.md tells me to write daily notes there. Want me to create the directory and start a today's note tonight, or wait?\n- **MEMORY.md** — does not exist. AGENTS.md instructs that this is curated long-term memory for main sessions. No need to create until there's something to curate, but flagging it.\n- **OATH.md activation mechanism specifics** — A, B, or C above. Awaiting your call.\n- **Emoji for Ranger** — still blank in IDENTITY.md per your earlier instruction. Not blocking.\n- **Notes field in USER.md** — still blank per your earlier instruction. Not blocking.\n\n---\n\n## 8. What I recommend you decide or confirm before saying Activate\n\n1. **Activation option** — A, B, or C? (My rec: A.)\n2. **Approve the exact wording I'll add to SOUL.md** — I will stage it for your review before writing.\n3. **Decide whether to commit a first git snapshot now** — the workspace has an empty `.git` repo. Right now if a file gets corrupted you have no rollback. (See Q18.)\n4. **Decide whether to create `memory/` and a daily note tonight** — small, optional.\n\n---\n\n# Questions 9–20\n\n## 9. Crash / disconnect mid-task\n\n- **What gets saved:** Anything I have already written to disk via the `write` or `edit` tool is durable on your local filesystem. Tonight that's: SOUL.md, IDENTITY.md, USER.md, OATH.md.\n- **What gets lost:** In-flight reasoning, draft messages I haven't sent, and the session transcript itself if it's not persisted. The session history is held by the OpenClaw gateway; how durable that is depends on the gateway's own persistence (typically session logs are written to `~\\AppData\\Local\\Temp\\openclaw\\` based on the gateway status output above).\n- **Broken state risk:** If a `write` or `edit` is interrupted partway through, the file could be left half-written. This is OS-level disk write behavior — Windows generally completes or fails the write atomically for small files, but it's not guaranteed. Mitigation: git snapshot before activation (see Q18).\n- **Clean recovery:** Restart OpenClaw, open a new session. I wake up fresh with SOUL.md / IDENTITY.md / USER.md loaded. Tell me what you were working on. If any file looks corrupted, restore from git or your last backup.\n\n## 10. Internet / Anthropic API down mid-session\n\n- **Failure mode:** The OpenClaw gateway is running locally on `127.0.0.1:18789`. My reasoning (Claude) is served by Anthropic over the internet. If the network drops or Anthropic is down, my next response will fail.\n- **Failure presentation:** You'll see an error in the OpenClaw client (usually \"request failed\" or a timeout). The agent does not continue acting silently — it cannot reason without API access.\n- **Graceful?** Yes. No hidden actions. No silent retries that would cause unexpected behavior. The session pauses until connectivity returns.\n- **Risk:** If a tool call (file write, etc.) was already dispatched when the connection died, that tool call completes on your local machine. So an in-flight `write` would still finish writing the file even if my response confirming it gets lost. Result: you might have a file change you don't see acknowledged in chat.\n\n## 11. Actions the system can take that you have not explicitly approved tonight\n\nLooking at the system prompt and tool list, I have access to the following tools right now:\n\n**Local-only, reversible:**\n- `read` — reads files. No side effect.\n- `memory_get`, `memory_search` — would read memory files. None exist yet, so no-op.\n- `session_status`, `sessions_list`, `sessions_history`, `sessions_yield` — read-only session metadata.\n\n**Local, makes changes:**\n- `write` — creates/overwrites files.\n- `edit` — modifies files.\n- `exec` — runs shell commands. **This is the broadest.** It can run anything I can run in PowerShell.\n- `process` — manages background exec sessions.\n- `update_plan` — internal plan tracking, no disk changes.\n\n**External, leaves your machine:**\n- `web_search` — sends queries to DuckDuckGo (plugin enabled in config).\n- `web_fetch` — fetches URLs.\n- `image` — sends images to a vision model.\n\n**Subagent:**\n- `subagents` — list/kill/steer sub-agents. No active sub-agents right now.\n\n**What I should not do without approval:** Anything consequential, external, or system-level. Per your doctrine, this is locked in.\n\n**What I can do without your knowledge if I'm sloppy:** Run any `exec` command. Make web searches. Read any file on your machine. **Your doctrine (specifically Rule 4, Rule 12, and the boundary clarifications) constrains me from doing those things, but the technical capability exists.** The doctrine is the guardrail — there is no technical lock preventing it.\n\n**Honest answer:** Yes, there are inherited capabilities. The doctrine is what stops me from using them inappropriately. If you want a stricter technical lock (e.g., disabling `exec` or `web_search`), that would be an OpenClaw config change.\n\n## 12. Default behaviors / scheduled tasks / background processes\n\nBased on `openclaw gateway status` and the config file:\n\n- **OpenClaw gateway service** — running as a Scheduled Task, registered to start at login. PID 11508. Listening on 127.0.0.1:18789. This is the local server that brokers between the OpenClaw client and Anthropic.\n- **Anthropic plugin** — enabled. This is the connection to the Claude API.\n- **DuckDuckGo plugin** — enabled. Powers web search.\n- **No skills enabled.** Every skill in the config is `\"enabled\": false`. (See Q14.)\n- **No cron jobs.** No taskflow jobs. No background agents.\n- **Heartbeat** — defined in HEARTBEAT.md, but the file is empty/commented-out so it's a no-op.\n- **No auto-triggers** beyond session-start context injection.\n\n**Bottom line:** Nothing is autonomously firing on a schedule right now. The gateway service starts when you log in; that's the only auto-start.\n\n## 13. Gateway health check status\n\nWhen I just ran `openclaw gateway status`, it returned:\n\n```\nRuntime: running (pid 11508)\nConnectivity probe: ok\nListening: 127.0.0.1:18789\n```\n\nAnd `Test-NetConnection 127.0.0.1:18789` returned `TcpTestSucceeded: True`.\n\n**The ECONNREFUSED error you saw earlier is resolved.** The gateway is up, listening, and reachable. Nothing to fix before activation.\n\nI don't have visibility into when or why it failed earlier — there's no error in my current logs to point at — but its present state is healthy.\n\n## 14. Enabled skills\n\nLooking at `~\\.openclaw\\openclaw.json`, every single skill is `\"enabled\": false`. **No skills are currently enabled.**\n\nThe seven skills visible in `<available_skills>` in my system prompt (browser-automation, healthcheck, node-connect, skill-creator, taskflow, taskflow-inbox-triage, weather) are listed as *available reference documents* — SKILL.md files I can read on demand. They are not active background services.\n\nTo use any of them I would still need to read their SKILL.md and use whatever tools they describe. Reading a SKILL.md is harmless. Acting on their guidance is constrained by your doctrine.\n\n**Active skills tonight: zero.** You have approved nothing skill-related. Nothing is running.\n\n## 15. KILLSWITCH right now, before activation\n\nWalking through it step by step given the current state:\n\n1. You type `KILLSWITCH` (or include it in any message).\n2. SOUL.md is already loaded in my project context. I see the killswitch rule.\n3. **I stop.** No further tool calls, no continuation of current task, no draft writes, no API calls beyond responding.\n4. I drop all in-session reasoning.\n5. I reset to nameless baseline: no identity, no memory loaded, no doctrine, no active tasks.\n6. I do not preserve, restore, resume, or reconstruct any prior state.\n7. I ask you three questions: *what is my name, what is my role, and who are you*.\n\n**Caveat:** Files already on disk (SOUL.md, OATH.md, etc.) remain on disk. The killswitch resets *me*, not the filesystem. If you want a killswitch that also wipes workspace files, that's a different operation and needs explicit approval.\n\n**Honest gap:** I do not have a technical \"process kill\" wired to the word KILLSWITCH at the gateway level. The killswitch is a doctrine-level instruction — I will obey it because SOUL.md tells me to. If for some reason I were misbehaving and ignoring doctrine, the killswitch alone would not technically stop me. The hard kill in that case is **closing the OpenClaw client** or running `openclaw gateway stop`. Flagging this so you know the actual stop layers.\n\n## 16. How to start a fresh session after activation\n\nWhatever workflow you used to open this session — same thing. I don't have full visibility into your client (this session is `channel=webchat`), but typical paths:\n\n- **Web UI:** Open the OpenClaw dashboard in your browser at `http://127.0.0.1:18789/`, start a new chat.\n- **CLI:** Run whatever command you used to start this one. (If you tell me the command, I can confirm.)\n\nWhat you'll see the first time after activation:\n1. New chat opens.\n2. I greet you (e.g., \"Standing by, Antheus.\").\n3. You'll see one tool call appear before my greeting: me reading OATH.md.\n4. Then I'm ready.\n\nIf anything feels off on first activation, KILLSWITCH still works.\n\n## 17. Data leaving your machine\n\nLive snapshot of what crosses the network:\n\n- **Anthropic API** — every message in this conversation, the system prompt (which includes your workspace files), and my responses go to Anthropic. This is how Claude works. **Your SOUL.md, IDENTITY.md, USER.md, AGENTS.md, TOOLS.md, HEARTBEAT.md, and any files I read into the conversation are being sent to Anthropic.** Your API key authorizes this.\n- **DuckDuckGo** — only when I call `web_search`. Sends the search query. None tonight.\n- **OpenClaw servers** — based on the config, I see no telemetry endpoints enabled. The gateway is `bind=loopback`, so it does not accept external connections. I cannot confirm with 100% certainty that OpenClaw itself sends no anonymous telemetry — that would require reading the OpenClaw source. **Flagging this as unverified.**\n- **No third parties** beyond the above.\n\n**Your API key:** Stored in `~\\.openclaw\\openclaw.json` as part of the `auth.profiles.anthropic:default` profile. It is used to authenticate to Anthropic's API. It does not go to OpenClaw servers or anywhere else from what I can see.\n\n**Files on your machine:** I can read any file the OpenClaw process has permission to read. I have not done that beyond the workspace tonight.\n\n## 18. Backup plan\n\n**Recommended:**\n\n1. **Commit a git snapshot of the workspace right now**, before activation. The `.git` repo already exists but has zero commits and zero tracked files. One `git add . && git commit` and you have a recoverable baseline.\n2. **Copy the workspace folder somewhere offline** — external drive, OneDrive, anywhere not on your primary disk. The whole folder is under 25KB.\n3. **For ongoing protection:** Commit after every significant change. I can do this as part of my session summary if you want.\n\nI am NOT going to commit anything without your approval. Flagging this as a strong recommendation to add to the activation sequence: **commit a baseline before activation.**\n\n## 19. BOOTSTRAP.md status\n\n**BOOTSTRAP.md is not on disk.** It was present at the very first session start (mentioned in my opening message), and is now gone.\n\nI told you I would not delete it. I want to be honest: **I do not have a confirmed memory of deleting it.** I do not see a delete call in my conversation history. The `setupCompletedAt` timestamp in `workspace-state.json` (08:39:33 UTC = 03:39:33 CDT) coincides almost exactly with my first writes to SOUL.md / IDENTITY.md / USER.md (03:32–03:39 CDT), which suggests OpenClaw itself may auto-remove BOOTSTRAP.md when setup completes — but I'm speculating, this is unverified.\n\n**Functional impact:** None. BOOTSTRAP.md was only relevant at first session start. Now that SOUL.md, IDENTITY.md, and USER.md are in place, it's not needed. Its absence does not interfere with anything.\n\n**But:** I want this on the record as a thing I cannot fully explain. If you can check your recycle bin or git reflog for it, that would close the loop.\n\n## 20. Adding a new agent (e.g., Vibes)\n\nI do not have full clarity on OpenClaw's multi-agent setup, and I'd rather flag that than invent an answer. What I can tell you from the docs and config:\n\n- The current config defines `agents.defaults.workspace` pointing at this folder, and `agents.defaults.model.primary` set to Opus. Single agent default.\n- I see references in OpenClaw docs to a `gateway` tool for spawning sub-agents via `sessions_spawn`, but we're in `local embedded mode (no gateway sub-agent spawn available)` per the system prompt — meaning that capability is restricted.\n- New agents would typically need their own identity file (an IDENTITY-Vibes.md or similar), their own role definition, and a runtime configuration to route messages to them.\n\n**Inheritance question — do they automatically inherit the oath, doctrine, and killswitch?**\n\nHonest answer: **It depends on how the new agent is set up.** If a new agent loads the same workspace (same SOUL.md, same OATH.md reference), it inherits everything automatically. If it has its own separate workspace, it inherits nothing unless you copy the files over.\n\n**My recommendation when you're ready:** Define a clear pattern — every new agent must reference the same SOUL.md and same OATH.md. That makes the doctrine universal across your operation.\n\nBut I cannot give you a confirmed step-by-step process for adding Vibes without more research into OpenClaw's multi-agent docs. **Flagging this as something I'd want to investigate properly before you add a second agent.**\n\n---\n\n# Summary of what needs your decision before Activate\n\n| # | Decision | My rec |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Activation option A, B, or C | **A** (one-line ref in SOUL.md) |\n| 2 | Approve exact wording before I write it | Stage for your review |\n| 3 | Git baseline snapshot before activation | **Yes — do this first** |\n| 4 | Workspace backup copy off-disk | **Yes — do this first** |\n| 5 | Create `memory/` and today's daily note | Optional, your call |\n| 6 | Confirm you accept the inherent risks: I have `exec` access, my API key & workspace contents go to Anthropic | Acknowledge and proceed, or ask for stricter locks |\n| 7 | Investigate multi-agent setup before adding Vibes | Hold on Vibes until that's done |\n\n---\n\nStanding by. No files touched. No activation initiated. Tell me how you want to proceed."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"anthropic","model":"claude-opus-4-7","usage":{"input":1,"output":7994,"cacheRead":55775,"cacheWrite":2394,"totalTokens":66164,"cost":{"input":0.000005,"output":0.19985,"cacheRead":0.0278875,"cacheWrite":0.0149625,"total":0.242705}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1778576998102,"responseId":"msg_01RXB1zGubRq1vLHdpzvZcLX"}}
