{"type":"message","id":"64e383d1","parentId":"67054c83","timestamp":"2026-05-12T09:26:24.278Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Confirmed what I needed. Answering your three questions straight.\n\n---\n\n## 1. What access OpenClaw currently has to your Windows filesystem\n\n**Answer: Full standard-user access. No sandbox. No container. No boundary.**\n\nThe OpenClaw gateway process runs as `desktop-5t523hi\\colem` — your own Windows user account. That means:\n\n- **I can read anything your user can read.** I just demonstrated this by listing your `C:\\Users\\colem\\Documents` (saw `highschool transcript.pdf` and others), `C:\\` root, and `C:\\Windows`. All succeeded.\n- **I can write anywhere your user has write permission.** Documents, Desktop, AppData, OneDrive folders, mounted drives, USB drives — anywhere standard-user write applies.\n- **I can execute any command your user can run** via the `exec` tool. PowerShell, command-line tools, any installed application. Same privileges as a normal user opening a terminal.\n- **I cannot do admin-level operations** (no `SeDebugPrivilege`, no `SeTakeOwnershipPrivilege`, no `SeBackupPrivilege`). I cannot modify system files, install services as admin, or touch protected OS resources without an elevation prompt — which would require you to click through UAC.\n\n**What I cannot do:**\n- Bypass UAC.\n- Read other user accounts' protected files.\n- Touch encrypted/EFS-protected files outside your account.\n- Modify Windows system files in `C:\\Windows\\System32` without admin elevation.\n\n**Bottom line:** Everything in your user profile, mapped drives, and shared folders is accessible. That includes Documents, Desktop, Downloads, Pictures, AppData, browser data, SSH keys, Windows credentials in your user store, and anything synced to OneDrive. There is no container preventing me from touching any of it. The only protection right now is your doctrine (SOUL.md) telling me not to — which is a behavi